subsection.p:
We would like to reverse the process and write a quadratic expression as the square of a binomial. For example, what constant term can we add to x^2 - 16x to produce a perfect square trinomial? Compare the expression to the formula above:
\begin{alignedat}{4} x^2 \amp {}+{} \amp 2px \amp {}+{} \amp p^2 \amp {}={} \amp (x + p)^2 \\ x^2 \amp {}-{} \amp 16x \amp {}+{} \amp \text{?} \amp {}={} \amp (x + \text{?})^2 \\ \end{alignedat}
We see that 2p = -16\text{, so }p = \frac{1}{2}(-16) = -8 and p^2 = (-8)^2 = 64 Substitute these values for p^2 and p into the equation to find x^2 - 16x + 64 = (x - 8)^2 Notice that in the resulting trinomial, the constant term is equal to the square of one-half the coefficient of x. In other words, we can find the constant term by taking one-half the coefficient of x and then squaring the result. Adding a constant term obtained in this way is called completing the squarecompleting the square.

statement.p:
Complete the square by adding an appropriate constant; write the result as the square of a binomial.



